# automation · Test Automation Rules
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# These rules apply ONLY to the automation/ directory.
# backend/ and frontend/ are separate projects and are unaffected.
#
# Directory layout:
#   automation/
#   ├── bootstrap/  ← env config, credentials (.env), auth setup
#   ├── core/       ← shared framework (api, fixtures, state)
#   ├── domains/    ← per-feature support: domains/{feature}/
#   ├── pages/      ← Page Object Models (flat)
#   └── suites/     ← test specs ONLY: suites/{feature}/*.spec.ts
#
# Skill files: automation/.cursor/skills/
# Workflows:   automation/.cursor/workflows/
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

## 0 · Token-efficiency gate (read this first on EVERY session)
- Before generating any test file, POM, or fixture: READ the matching skill file
  from .cursor/skills/ first. Never produce a pattern from memory when a skill file exists.
- Never regenerate a file that already passes `npm run validate:conventions` without explicit user instruction.
- Test generation: ONE file per response. Ask before continuing to the next file.
- Before rewriting a file: diff first. If the change is < 5 lines, use StrReplace only.
  Never do a full-file rewrite for minor changes.
- Skill files are the authoritative source of truth. When a skill file conflicts with
  training-data knowledge, the skill file wins.

## 1 · Project structure rules
- All POM files live in `automation/pages/` (flat — no sub-folders).
  File naming: `{FeatureName}Page.ts`   e.g. LoginPage.ts, ProductListPage.ts
- All test files live in `automation/suites/{feature}/api/` or `suites/{feature}/ui/`.
  File naming: `{feature}.api.spec.ts` / `{feature}.ui.spec.ts`
- Feature support code lives in `automation/domains/{feature}/`:
  `{feature}.schemas.ts` (Zod response schemas only),
  `{feature}.api-errors.ts` (HTTP error contracts),
  `{feature}.ui-messages.ts` (inline errors, toasts, banners),
  `{feature}.fixture.ts` (Playwright fixtures),
  `{Feature}RequestBuilder.ts` (optional)
- Test credentials live in `.env` — read via `@bootstrap/credentials` only. Never hardcode in domains or specs.
- Core (framework, not tests): `automation/core/`
- DO NOT create `e2e/` sub-folders. Hybrid API+UI tests go in `ui/` spec files
  using `test.beforeEach` with `foundryAPI` for setup.

## 2 · TypeScript
- Strict mode everywhere: `strict: true`, `exactOptionalPropertyTypes: true`.
- Never use `any`. Use `unknown` and narrow explicitly.
- Target ES2022+; `async/await` only — no `.then()` chains in test bodies.
- Path aliases: `@bootstrap/*`, `@core/*`, `@pages/*`, `@domains/*`, `@suites/*`.
- `tsc --noEmit` must pass before committing.

## 3 · POM rules (`automation/pages/`)
- Every POM extends `BasePage` from `pages/BasePage.ts`.
- Constructor: `constructor(page: Page)` — no ctx, no UiActions instance needed.
- BasePage already provides all interaction methods: `this.fillInput(...)`,
  `this.clickElement(...)`, `this.assertVisible(...)`, etc.
- All locators are **private getters** returning `this.page.locator(...)`.
  Selector priority (strict):
    1. `[data-testid="value"]`           ← always first
    2. `#stableId`                       ← skip auto-generated IDs
    3. `form [name="value"]`             ← for form inputs
    4. `[aria-label="value"]`            ← accessible elements
    5. Relative CSS path (≤ 3 levels)   ← last resort
- NEVER use `getByLabel()` or `getByRole()` in a POM.
- All public POM methods are `async`, return `Promise<void>`.
- Interaction methods inherited from BasePage are `protected` — call them as
  `this.fillInput(...)`, `this.clickElement(...)`, NOT via a separate instance.

## 4 · Spec file rules (`automation/suites/`)
- Import `test` and `expect` from the domain fixture (e.g. `@domains/auth/auth.fixture`),
  NEVER from `@playwright/test` directly.
- NEVER import `Page` in a test file — use POM methods only.
- Every spec file MUST contain at least one `test.describe()`.
- Every `test()` block MUST contain at least one `expect()` assertion.
  `expect(res).toBeDefined()` alone is NOT a valid assertion.
- All test phases MUST be wrapped in `test.step('description', async () => { })`.
- Test naming MUST follow the pattern:
    `test('[CamelCaseName] | verify that <expected behaviour>', ...)`
  Examples:
    `test('[LoginWithValidCredentials] | verify that valid credentials redirect to dashboard', ...)`
    `test('[EmptyEmail] | verify that submitting without email shows a validation message', ...)`
  Rules:
    - `[CamelCaseName]` is short (1–3 words), PascalCase, describes the scenario.
    - The part after ` | ` MUST start with "verify that".
    - No TC-XXX codes, no dashes, no `@tag` prefixes in the test title.

## 5 · Anti-patterns (hard block)
- `page.waitForTimeout(N)` — BANNED. Use `expect(locator).toBeVisible()`.
- `waitForNetworkIdle()` — allowed ONLY with a comment explaining why.
- Hardcoded passwords/tokens → `.env` + `@bootstrap/credentials`. Intentional invalid values in negative tests are OK inline.
- Sequential `await` in a loop for independent API calls → `Promise.all()`.
- `nth-child()` / `nth-of-type()` in selectors.
- Generated CSS class names (css-*, sc-*, chakra-*) in selectors.

## 6 · API layer rules
- `FoundryAPI` is the ONLY way to call API endpoints in tests.
  Usage: `const res = await foundryAPI.User.v1UserActivityGet()`
- The `axios` package may only be imported in `core/api/generated/index.ts`
  and `core/fixtures/base.fixture.ts` (worker login). Nowhere else.
- After running `npm run swagger:api`, `core/api/generated/index.ts` is
  auto-replaced by the OpenAPI-generated client. Do not manually edit it.
- Every API test MUST call `ApiAssertions.assertStatus(res, N)` + one body assertion.
  For 4xx with known messages use `ApiAssertions.assertErrorResponse(res, status, schema, message)`.
- Request bodies: use strongly-typed parameters from the generated client.
  Multiple body shapes use discriminated unions — never `any`.

## 7 · FoundryAPI namespace addition workflow
When a new API group is added to the spec:
  1. Re-run `npm run swagger:api`
  2. Import the new class in `core/api/FoundryAPI.ts`
  3. Add `readonly NewGroup: NewGroupApi;` property
  4. Instantiate in the constructor
  That's it — tests can immediately use `foundryAPI.NewGroup.*`.

## 8 · Auth / setup rules
- `core/fixtures/auth.setup.ts` is the ONLY place browser login happens.
  It runs as the `setup` project and writes `.auth-state.json`.
- All browser test projects depend on `setup` and read storageState from
  `.auth-state.json`. Tests never log in via the UI themselves.
- For API-auth in `foundryAPI`: the `apiToken` worker fixture does a single
  API login per worker. Tests use `foundryAPI` directly.
- `.auth-state.json` is gitignored — never commit it.

## 9 · StateManager rules
- Store ONLY `{ id, createdAt, meta? }` — never full response payloads.
- `state.get('key')` throws if missing (fail-fast). Use `getOrNull` for optional.
- `state.reset()` is called automatically in `afterEach` by the base fixture.
  Never call it manually. Never create `new StateManager()` in test bodies.

## 10 · Fixture rules
- `base.fixture.ts` exports: `foundryAPI`, `state`, `testContext`, `pageFactory`, `testPage`.
- Domain fixtures extend `baseTest` and add their POMs:
  `loginPage: async ({ page }, use) => { await use(new LoginPage(page)); }`
- Worker-scoped: `apiToken` (single API login per worker).
- `testContext` is `auto:true` — do not reference it explicitly in tests.

## 11 · Memory-leak & race-condition prevention
- Event listeners registered in tests → removed in `afterEach`.
- No closures capturing `Page` or `Browser` outside fixture scope.
- Large API payloads → store only IDs.
- Parallel-isolation: `AsyncLocalStorage` for token, fresh `StateManager` per test,
  cookies/storage cleared in `testPage` afterEach.

## 12 · CI & parallelism
- `fullyParallel: true` always.
- Unique test data: `const uid = \`${Date.now()}-${Math.random().toString(36).slice(2,7)}\``.
- Run a single feature: `npx playwright test --grep @auth`.
- Never `{ workers: N }` hardcoded — CI sets it via `--workers`.

## 13 · Naming & import order
- Imports: Node builtins → npm packages → `@playwright/test` → `@bootstrap/*` → `@core/*` → `@pages/*`
  → `@domains/*` → `@suites/*` → relative.
- No barrel re-exports (no `index.ts` that re-exports everything).
- Named imports only; no default imports except for framework defaults.
